What rules of conduct apply
in this rural situation?

249
00:22:41,387 --> 00:22:44,129
We have been introduced, have we not?

250
00:22:45,191 --> 00:22:49,901
What value is there in an introduction
when you cannot even remember my name?

251
00:22:50,029 --> 00:22:53,305
Indeed, can barely stay awake in my presence.

252
00:22:55,201 --> 00:22:56,402
Madam.

253
00:22:56,402 --> 00:23:00,139
These scruples must seem very provincial
to a gentleman with such elevated airs,

254
00:23:00,139 --> 00:23:04,280
but I do not devise these rules.
I am merely obliged to obey them.

255
00:23:06,112 --> 00:23:09,615
I have been told
there is much to see upon a walk

256
00:23:09,615 --> 00:23:14,120
but all I've detected so far is a general
tendency to green above and brown below.

257
00:23:14,120 --> 00:23:18,057
Yes, well, others have detected more.
It is celebrated.

258
00:23:18,057 --> 00:23:21,163
-There's even a book about Selborne Wood.
-Oh.

259
00:23:22,595 --> 00:23:24,267
A novel, perhaps?

260
00:23:27,066 --> 00:23:28,340
Novels?

261
00:23:30,069 --> 00:23:35,408
Being poor, insipid things, read by mere women,
even, God forbid, written by mere women?

262
00:23:35,408 --> 00:23:37,076
I see, we're talking ofyour reading.

263
00:23:37,076 --> 00:23:41,180
As ifthe writing ofwomen did not display
the greatest powers of mind,

264
00:23:41,180 --> 00:23:44,650
knowledge of human nature,
the liveliest effusions ofwit and humour

265
00:23:44,650 --> 00:23:47,620
and the best-chosen language imaginable?

266
00:23:47,620 --> 00:23:50,691
-Was I deficient in rapture?
-In consciousness.

267
00:23:51,924 --> 00:23:53,528
It was...

268
00:23:56,829 --> 00:24:00,105
It was accomplished.

269
00:24:07,007 --> 00:24:08,542
It was ironic.

270
00:24:13,780 --> 00:24:17,227
-And you're sure I've not offended you?
-Not at all.

271
00:24:28,962 --> 00:24:33,240
My lords, ladies and gentlemen,
the Grand Vizier's Flight.

272
00:24:37,337 --> 00:24:40,545
-May I have the honour?
-How kind, cousin.

273
00:24:48,381 --> 00:24:50,986
-Miss Austen.
-Mr Wisley.

274
00:24:51,985 --> 00:24:54,988
May I have the pleasure ofthis next dance?

275
00:24:57,090 --> 00:24:58,899
(CHATTERING)

276
00:25:01,094 --> 00:25:03,938
LUCY: Oh, no, we're so late.
MRS LEFROY: Take care.

277
00:25:04,231 --> 00:25:05,999
Oh, thank you, Tom.

278
00:25:05,999 --> 00:25:07,205
LUCY: Hurry.
MRS LEFROY: Lucy.

279
00:25:26,019 --> 00:25:27,220
(EXCLAIMS)

280
00:25:27,220 --> 00:25:28,426
WISLEY: Oh!

281
00:25:33,226 --> 00:25:34,796
I am mortified.

282
00:25:36,296 --> 00:25:39,242
I practised, but it won't stick.

283
00:25:49,409 --> 00:25:51,286
HENRY: What a lovely pair they make.

284
00:25:53,280 --> 00:25:54,915
Ah, Sister.

285
00:25:54,915 --> 00:25:58,618
ELIZA: What do you make of Mr Lefroy?
JANE: We're honoured by his presence.

286
00:25:58,618 --> 00:25:59,753
You think?

287
00:25:59,753 --> 00:26:02,455
He does, with his preening, prancing,
Irish-cum-Bond-Street airs.

288
00:26:02,455 --> 00:26:03,657
Jane.

289
00:26:03,657 --> 00:26:07,627
Well, I call it very high indeed, refusing
to dance when there are so few gentleman.

290
00:26:07,627 --> 00:26:10,297
-Henry, are all your friends so disagreeable?
-Jane.

291
00:26:10,297 --> 00:26:12,465
Where exactly in Ireland
does he come from, anyway?

292
00:26:12,465 --> 00:26:14,342
Limerick, Miss Austen.

293
00:26:21,975 --> 00:26:25,178
I would regard it as a mark of extreme favour

294
00:26:25,178 --> 00:26:28,750
ifyou would stoop
to honour me with this next dance.

295
00:26:30,116 --> 00:26:32,994
(COUNTRY DANCE MUSIC PLAYING)

296
00:26:34,321 --> 00:26:38,458
Being the first to dance with me, madam,
I feel it only fair to inform you

297
00:26:38,458 --> 00:26:41,962
that you carry the standard
for Hampshire hospitality.

298
00:26:41,962 --> 00:26:45,332
Ah, then your country reputation
depends on my report.

299
00:26:45,332 --> 00:26:50,110
This, by the way, is called a country dance,
after the French, contredanse.

300
00:26:53,607 --> 00:26:57,344
Not because it is exhibited
at an uncouth rural assembly

301
00:26:57,344 --> 00:26:59,118
with glutinous pies,

302
00:27:01,848 --> 00:27:03,349
execrable Madeira

303
00:27:05,118 --> 00:27:06,820
and truly anarchic dancing.

304
00:27:06,820 --> 00:27:09,232
You judge the company severely, madam.

305
00:27:09,623 --> 00:27:12,959
-I was describing what you'd be thinking.
-Allow me to think for myself.

306
00:27:12,959 --> 00:27:16,296
Gives me leave to do the same, sir,
and come to a different conclusion.

307
00:27:16,296 --> 00:27:20,066
-Will you give so much to a woman?
-It must depend on the woman

308
00:27:20,066 --> 00:27:22,136
and what she thinks of me.

309
00:27:23,403 --> 00:27:27,510
But you are above being pleased.

310
00:27:30,010 --> 00:27:32,379
And I think that you, miss, what was it?

311
00:27:32,379 --> 00:27:34,825
-Austen. Mr...?
-Lefroy.

312
00:27:36,750 --> 00:27:42,700
I think that you, Miss Austen,
consider yourself a cut above the company.

313
00:27:44,357 --> 00:27:45,494
Me?

314
00:27:47,694 --> 00:27:49,366
You, ma'am,

315
00:27:50,330 --> 00:27:52,571
secretly.

316
00:27:54,434 --> 00:27:56,174
(ALL APPLAUDING)

317
00:28:02,442 --> 00:28:06,414
How many times did you stand up
with that gentleman, Jane?

318
00:28:06,414 --> 00:28:08,449
-LUCY: Was it twice?
-Twice would have been partial.

319
00:28:08,449 --> 00:28:11,218
-Thrice would have been absolutely...
-LUCY: Flagrant.

320
00:28:11,218 --> 00:28:15,690
Careful, Jane, Lucy is right.
Mr Lefroy does have a reputation.

321
00:28:15,690 --> 00:28:18,259
Presumably as the most disagreeable...

322
00:28:18,259 --> 00:28:22,366
"...insoIent, arrogant, impudent,

323
00:28:23,230 --> 00:28:28,975
"insufferabIe, impertinent of men."

324
00:28:35,743 --> 00:28:37,620
Too many adjectives.

325
00:28:51,058 --> 00:28:53,162
What is she trying to say?

326
00:28:53,761 --> 00:28:56,400
On your toes, gentlemen. No singles.

327
00:28:58,666 --> 00:28:59,834
(GRUNTS)

328
00:28:59,834 --> 00:29:01,176
(ALL CHEERING)

329
00:29:01,435 --> 00:29:03,505
Bowler's end, bowler's end.

330
00:29:07,341 --> 00:29:09,343
MAN 1 : Again!
MAN 2: Run for more.

331
00:29:09,343 --> 00:29:12,449
I never feel more French
than when I watch cricket.

332
00:29:14,181 --> 00:29:15,349
-Out.
-Not out.

333
00:29:15,349 --> 00:29:16,517
-No?
-No.

334
00:29:16,517 --> 00:29:18,189
MRS AUSTEN: Is he out?

335
00:29:23,591 --> 00:29:26,827
I begin to suspect
you're flirting with my brother, cousin.

336
00:29:26,827 --> 00:29:30,775
Flirting is a woman's trade.
One must keep in practice.

337
00:29:31,999 --> 00:29:33,167
(EXCLAIMS)

338
00:29:33,167 --> 00:29:34,543
You're gone.

339
00:29:35,002 --> 00:29:36,674
MAN: Well played, Tom.

340
00:29:38,839 --> 00:29:41,012
We're depending on you.

341
00:29:42,943 --> 00:29:44,683
MRS AUSTEN: Oh, it's Mr Warren's...turn.

342
00:29:46,280 --> 00:29:47,715
MAN: Best of luck!

343
00:29:47,715 --> 00:29:49,194
John Warren!

344
00:29:50,718 --> 00:29:52,527
MAN: Good luck, Mr Warren.

345
00:29:53,020 --> 00:29:55,329
John neverwas very good, though.

346
00:30:07,234 --> 00:30:08,974
MAN: Easy!

347
00:30:10,971 --> 00:30:12,506
MAN: Run, Warren, run!

348
00:30:12,506 --> 00:30:13,908
MAN 1 : Quickly, hurry!
MAN 2: Run!

349
00:30:13,908 --> 00:30:15,580
Jolly good show!

350
00:30:16,377 --> 00:30:17,651
Watch.

351
00:30:19,346 --> 00:30:21,015
-UMPIRE: You're out.
-Yah!

352
00:30:21,015 --> 00:30:22,683
-UMPIRE: You're gone, Mr Warren.
-Oh, dear.

353
00:30:22,683 --> 00:30:24,560
Prodigious, Tom, prodigious.

354
00:30:25,319 --> 00:30:26,593
(LAUGHING)

355
00:30:28,189 --> 00:30:30,224
Thank you, Warren. On yourway.

356
00:30:30,224 --> 00:30:31,862
MAN: Same again, Tom.

357
00:30:34,195 --> 00:30:38,098
-MRS AUSTEN: Well done, Mr Warren.
-Bad ball. It's a terrible wicket.

358
00:30:38,098 --> 00:30:41,374
I hope you're not too disappointed, Miss Austen.

359
00:30:42,670 --> 00:30:44,615
Four more to win, Wisley.

360
00:30:46,574 --> 00:30:48,917
MAN 1 : Who's next?
MAN 2: Come on!

361
00:30:50,110 --> 00:30:51,745
-LUCY: She can't...
-Jane!

362
00:30:51,745 --> 00:30:54,348
What on earth are you going to do?

363
00:30:54,348 --> 00:30:56,717
WOMAN 1 : Irrepressible.
WOMAN 2: ...she can.

364
00:30:56,717 --> 00:30:58,423
(CROWD APPLAUDING)

365
00:31:09,630 --> 00:31:10,938
MAN 1 : Move in!

366
00:31:11,932 --> 00:31:13,433
MAN 2: Go easy, Tom.

367
00:31:18,472 --> 00:31:20,281
MAN 3: Be gentle, Lefroy!

368
00:31:37,625 --> 00:31:38,933
(GRUNTS)

369
00:31:40,928 --> 00:31:42,236
(ALL EXCLAIM)

370
00:31:42,563 --> 00:31:44,732
Run, Jane, run!

371
00:31:44,732 --> 00:31:46,768
-Move!
-Run!

372
00:31:48,235 --> 00:31:50,009
Only four more to win.

373
00:31:50,404 --> 00:31:52,975
MAN: Bowler's end! Move yourself, you lout!

374
00:31:56,410 --> 00:31:58,355
MAN: One more!
WOMAN: Quickly!

375
00:31:58,913 --> 00:32:00,414
Go, go, go!

376
00:32:00,414 --> 00:32:01,756
UMPIRE: Not out.

377
00:32:04,786 --> 00:32:06,026
Bad luck, Lefroy.

378
00:32:11,293 --> 00:32:12,430
See?

379
00:32:16,831 --> 00:32:18,503
WOMAN: She was so good.

380
00:32:23,305 --> 00:32:27,442
-You've played this game before?
-No choice, you see. She was raised by brothers.

381
00:32:27,442 --> 00:32:29,512
Time for a swim, I think.

382
00:32:33,682 --> 00:32:35,183
MRS AUSTEN: Well played, Henry.

383
00:32:35,183 --> 00:32:38,459
I dedicate our victory to La Comtesse de Feuillide.

384
00:32:42,157 --> 00:32:45,627
-Now, there's a decent bit of river over the hill.
-Oh, yes?

385
00:32:46,828 --> 00:32:48,534
(EXCLAIMING)

386
00:32:51,032 --> 00:32:52,340
Careful!

387
00:33:10,085 --> 00:33:11,689
Come on, let's go!

388
00:33:13,555 --> 00:33:14,761
Wait!

389
00:33:19,260 --> 00:33:21,763
-Not this time, Lefroy.
-Huh?

390
00:33:21,763 --> 00:33:23,071
You think not?

391
00:33:29,170 --> 00:33:30,444
(WHOOPING)

392
00:33:48,256 --> 00:33:49,424
(DOG BARKS)

393
00:33:49,424 --> 00:33:50,766
Down, boy.

394
00:33:53,261 --> 00:33:56,640
-Father, have you seen Tom?
-No, Lucy, I've not.

395
00:34:01,603 --> 00:34:06,142
Besotted. Natural enough at 15.

396
00:34:06,875 --> 00:34:09,411
Love and sense are enemies at any age.

397
00:34:09,411 --> 00:34:13,552
-Mrs Lefroy, may I explore your library?
-Of course.

398
00:34:15,083 --> 00:34:19,320
Lucy would marry him tomorrow,
and what a terrible husband he would make.

399
00:34:19,320 --> 00:34:24,064
I suppose you mean his reputation.
Experience can recommend a man.

400
00:34:43,978 --> 00:34:46,117
(MAN CHUCKLING)

401
00:35:04,332 --> 00:35:07,642
-Miss Austen.
-Oh, Mr Lefroy.

402
00:35:09,604 --> 00:35:12,311
-And reading.
-Yes.

403
00:35:12,941 --> 00:35:16,678
I've been looking through your book ofthe wood.
MeWhite's NaturaI History.

404
00:35:16,678 --> 00:35:17,781
Oh.

405
00:35:18,279 --> 00:35:22,022
-Well, how do you like it?
-I cannot get on. It is too disturbing.

406
00:35:22,450 --> 00:35:24,020
-Disturbing?
-Mmm.

407
00:35:25,220 --> 00:35:27,622
Take this observation.

408
00:35:27,622 --> 00:35:28,823
(CLEARS THROAT)

409
00:35:28,823 --> 00:35:33,465
"Swifts on a fine morning in May,
flying this way, that way,

410
00:35:33,661 --> 00:35:37,870
"sailing around at a great height
perfectly happily. Then...

411
00:35:38,533 --> 00:35:43,872
"Then one leaps onto the back of another,
grasps tightly,

412
00:35:43,872 --> 00:35:50,414
"and forgetting to fly, they both sink
down and down in a great, dying fall,

413
00:35:51,379 --> 00:35:55,520
"fathom after fathom, until the female utters..."

414
00:36:01,156 --> 00:36:02,225
Yes?

415
00:36:06,328 --> 00:36:10,606
"...the female utters a loud, piercing cry

416
00:36:13,869 --> 00:36:15,109
"of ecstasy."

417
00:36:20,509 --> 00:36:24,115
Is this conduct commonplace
in the natural history of Hampshire?

418
00:36:26,849 --> 00:36:27,918
(STUTTERS)

419
00:36:29,618 --> 00:36:35,466
Your ignorance is understandable
since you lack... What shall we call it?

420
00:36:37,193 --> 00:36:38,364
The history?

421
00:36:40,896 --> 00:36:44,233
Propriety commands me to ignorance.

422
00:36:44,233 --> 00:36:49,079
Condemns you to it and yourwriting
to the status offemale accomplishment.

423
00:36:49,905 --> 00:36:55,081
Ifyou wish to practise the art offiction,
to be the equal of a masculine author,

424
00:36:55,444 --> 00:36:58,049
experience is vital.

425
00:37:00,950 --> 00:37:02,156
I see.

426
00:37:03,652 --> 00:37:08,157
And what qualifies you to offer this advice?

427
00:37:08,958 --> 00:37:10,292
I know more of the world.

428
00:37:10,292 --> 00:37:11,927
(LAUGHS SARCASTICALLY)

429
00:37:11,927 --> 00:37:14,339
A great deal more, I gather.

430
00:37:15,831 --> 00:37:20,677
Enough to know
that your horizons must be...widened

431
00:37:23,239 --> 00:37:25,343
by an extraordinary young man.

432
00:37:25,975 --> 00:37:28,811
By a very dangerous young man,

433
00:37:28,811 --> 00:37:31,780
one who has, no doubt,
infected the hearts of many a young...

434
00:37:31,780 --> 00:37:35,455
-Young woman with the soft corruption...
-Read this

435
00:37:36,852 --> 00:37:38,592
and you will understand.

436
00:37:45,928 --> 00:37:50,843
"When the phiIosopher heard that the fortress
of virtue had aIready been subdued,

437
00:37:51,133 --> 00:37:54,273
"he began to give a Iarge scope to his desires.

438
00:37:54,470 --> 00:37:58,440
"His appetite was not of that squeamish kind
which cannot feed on a dainty

439
00:37:58,440 --> 00:38:00,276
-"because another..."
-TOM: "Another has tasted it."

440
00:38:00,276 --> 00:38:04,189
-He's not tasting this dainty.
-What, dear?

441
00:38:05,114 --> 00:38:07,983
JANE: "...nor had her face
much appearance of beauty.

442
00:38:07,983 --> 00:38:11,520
"But her cIothes being torn
from aII the upper part of her body..."

443
00:38:11,520 --> 00:38:16,127
TOM: "...her breasts, which were well formed
and extremeIy white,

444
00:38:16,692 --> 00:38:21,497
"attracted the eyes of her deIiverer,
and for a few moments they stood siIent..."

445
00:38:21,497 --> 00:38:23,567
JANE: "...and gazing at each other."

446
00:38:36,245 --> 00:38:38,816
(CHURCH BELL TOLLING)

447
00:38:48,023 --> 00:38:50,230
I have read your book.

448
00:38:51,827 --> 00:38:55,240
-I have read your book and disapprove.
-Of course you do.

449
00:38:55,764 --> 00:39:01,839
-But ofwhat? The scenes? Characters? The prose?
-No, all good.

450
00:39:03,539 --> 00:39:06,019
-The morality?
-Flawed.

451
00:39:06,542 --> 00:39:09,712
(LAUGHING) Well, of course, it is. But why?

452
00:39:09,712 --> 00:39:14,049
Vice leads to difficulty, virtue to reward.
Bad characters come to bad ends.

453
00:39:14,049 --> 00:39:19,688
Exactly. But in life, bad characters often thrive.
Take yourself.

454
00:39:19,688 --> 00:39:20,856
(TOM LAUGHING)

455
00:39:20,856 --> 00:39:25,031
And a novel must show how the world truly is,

456
00:39:25,260 --> 00:39:29,365
how characters genuinely think,
how events actually occur.

457
00:39:29,365 --> 00:39:34,974
A novel should somehow reveal
the true source of our actions.

458
00:39:37,306 --> 00:39:39,149
What of my hero's feelings?

459
00:39:39,575 --> 00:39:44,380
Well, it seems to me, sir,
that your hero's very vigorous feelings

460
00:39:44,380 --> 00:39:47,716
caused him and everyone connected with him
a great deal oftrouble.

461
00:39:47,716 --> 00:39:50,253
Ah, well, ifthe book has troubled you...

462
00:39:50,586 --> 00:39:54,056
-Oh, but an orphan must know trouble.
-What sort of trouble?

463
00:39:54,890 --> 00:39:56,664
All sorts of trouble.

464
00:40:06,169 --> 00:40:09,839
Laverton Fair. Vastly entertaining.
Monstrous good idea, Jane.

465
00:40:09,839 --> 00:40:13,243
Yes, Miss Austen, not exactly
your usual society, I'd say.

466
00:40:13,243 --> 00:40:15,620
Show a little imagination, Mr Lefroy.

467
00:40:45,375 --> 00:40:48,078
Trouble here enough.

468
00:40:48,078 --> 00:40:51,058
And freedom, the freedom of men.

469
00:40:51,448 --> 00:40:53,283
Do not you envy it?

470
00:40:53,283 --> 00:40:57,162
But I have the intense pleasure
of observing it so closely.

471
00:41:00,824 --> 00:41:01,991
Ah.

472
00:41:01,991 --> 00:41:05,062
Now, there's a fool,
to go to it with a professional.

473
00:41:05,295 --> 00:41:06,729
(GRUNTING)

474
00:41:06,729 --> 00:41:09,835
-You know about this, of course.
-Of course.

475
00:41:09,966 --> 00:41:12,912
Yes, a vastly fashionable pastime in London.

476
00:41:20,910 --> 00:41:23,822
Beating a man to a pulp. What are you doing?

477
00:41:26,449 --> 00:41:28,758
Mr Lefroy, stop!

478
00:41:29,185 --> 00:41:30,459
TOM: Make way!

479
00:41:31,754 --> 00:41:33,289
(GRUNTING)

480
00:41:34,991 --> 00:41:38,199
-Stop!
-Let us see how you fare against me, sir.

481
00:41:39,195 --> 00:41:40,503
Coming through.

482
00:41:44,834 --> 00:41:49,180
Five shillings on the gent. Who will take it?
You, sir? That's the ticket.

483
00:41:51,307 --> 00:41:52,547
Have that.

484
00:41:54,377 --> 00:41:55,480
Thank you.

485
00:41:55,812 --> 00:41:57,655
Go on, hit him!

486
00:42:00,049 --> 00:42:02,529
Come on, Lefroy, hit him, man!

487
00:42:03,186 --> 00:42:07,134
Tom, you must stop.

488
00:42:10,393 --> 00:42:11,997
Come on, Lefroy!

489
00:42:14,964 --> 00:42:16,374
Up, sir.

490
00:42:19,302 --> 00:42:20,508
Tom!

491
00:42:21,504 --> 00:42:22,710
(EXCLAIMS)

492
00:42:23,072 --> 00:42:24,551
Lucy.

493
00:42:26,075 --> 00:42:27,815
(EXCLAIMING)

494
00:42:30,213 --> 00:42:34,320
-That's twice he's done that to me.
-You spend money like water.

495
00:42:35,485 --> 00:42:37,988
I'm afraid it's damn low waterwith me.

496
00:42:38,154 --> 00:42:40,497
-I'm afraid I'm short, sir.
-Take it.

497
00:42:42,058 --> 00:42:43,832
How embarrassing.

498
00:42:45,528 --> 00:42:46,665
Yeh!

499
00:42:47,230 --> 00:42:50,905
Mr Lefroy? Mr Lefroy? Mr Lefroy?

500
00:42:56,439 --> 00:42:58,680
Was I deficient in propriety?

501
00:43:01,377 --> 00:43:03,447
Why did you do that?

502
00:43:04,280 --> 00:43:07,556
Couldn't waste
all those expensive boxing lessons.

503
00:43:10,620 --> 00:43:13,189
Forgive me if I suspect in you a sense of justice.

504
00:43:13,189 --> 00:43:15,032
(CHUCKLING)

505
00:43:17,894 --> 00:43:21,898
I am a lawyer. Justice plays no part in the law.

506
00:43:23,466 --> 00:43:25,240
Is that what you believe?

507
00:43:28,204 --> 00:43:29,739
I believe it. I must.

508
00:43:33,776 --> 00:43:35,220
I beg your leave.

509
00:43:44,153 --> 00:43:48,101
-Her heart is stirred.
-It's a summer squall.

510
00:43:48,458 --> 00:43:54,636
Mr Lefroy will soon be gone.
And Mr Wisley will still be waiting, I hope.

511
00:43:55,298 --> 00:43:58,635
-The man's a booby.
-Oh, he will grow out ofthat.

512
00:43:58,635 --> 00:44:01,446
And she could fix him with very little trouble.

513
00:44:01,572 --> 00:44:04,408
You could persuade her.

514
00:44:04,408 --> 00:44:06,012
To sacrifice her happiness?

515
00:44:06,510 --> 00:44:11,615
Jane should have not the man
who offers the best price, but the man she wants.

516
00:44:11,615 --> 00:44:13,287
Oh, Mr Austen.

517
00:44:13,851 --> 00:44:17,921
Must we have this conversation
day in and day out?

518
00:44:17,921 --> 00:44:21,300
We'll end up in the gutter ifwe carry on like this.

519
00:44:38,542 --> 00:44:42,114
MRS AUSTEN: Jenny! Mr Austen!

520
00:44:44,214 --> 00:44:45,522
Where are you?

521
00:44:54,191 --> 00:44:55,533
(DOORBELL DINGS)

522
00:45:10,708 --> 00:45:13,051
So kind ofyou to return the call.

523
00:45:17,414 --> 00:45:20,588
-Will you take a dish oftea, ma'am?
-Green tea?

524
00:45:21,518 --> 00:45:24,897
-Brown, Your Ladyship.
-Then no.

525
00:45:30,828 --> 00:45:32,864
Where is your youngest daughter?

526
00:45:34,431 --> 00:45:36,911
She's visiting the poor, ma'am.

527
00:45:49,246 --> 00:45:52,625
Jane? Jane!

528
00:45:55,052 --> 00:46:01,799
At last. Lady Gresham and Mr Wisley
have come to call. Where have you been?

529
00:46:03,694 --> 00:46:05,195
Ma'am. Sir.

530
00:46:06,864 --> 00:46:11,468
Well, perhaps... Perhaps the young people
would like to take a walk?

531
00:46:11,468 --> 00:46:15,381
I see there's a pretty little wilderness
at the side of the house.

532
00:46:16,974 --> 00:46:18,384
Excuse me.

533
00:46:22,880 --> 00:46:24,290
Jane?

534
00:46:27,751 --> 00:46:30,128
-What is she doing?
-Writing.

535
00:46:32,122 --> 00:46:34,124
Can anything be done about it?

536
00:46:39,596 --> 00:46:43,000
Miss Austen, you may know

537
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:46,003
that I have known you

538
00:46:46,003 --> 00:46:50,073
for some considerable time
during my visits to Steventon.

539
00:46:50,073 --> 00:46:54,817
The garden is so affecting in this season.

540
00:46:55,746 --> 00:46:56,986
Indeed.

541
00:46:57,481 --> 00:47:02,657
-The impression you have given me has always...
-The flowers particularly.

542
00:47:03,420 --> 00:47:06,690
What I'm trying to say is that I...

543
00:47:06,690 --> 00:47:09,126
I have a respectable property of 2,000 a year

544
00:47:09,126 --> 00:47:12,029
in addition to even greater expectations
as Lady Gresham's heir,

545
00:47:12,029 --> 00:47:15,933
-to which it may be indelicate to refer.
-Oh, indelicate, yes.

546
00:47:15,933 --> 00:47:19,937
It's yours. Ifwe marry, all of it, yours.

547
00:47:23,674 --> 00:47:25,278
Mr Wisley...

548
00:47:30,113 --> 00:47:36,552
Your offer is most sincere, I can see,
and gentlemanlike, and it honours me, truly.

549
00:47:38,322 --> 00:47:43,066
But for all you are, and all you offer, I...

550
00:47:45,295 --> 00:47:46,364
Yes.

551
00:47:49,833 --> 00:47:51,243
(CLEARS THROAT)

552
00:47:57,541 --> 00:48:01,148
Sometimes affection is a shy flower
that takes time to blossom.

553
00:48:08,219 --> 00:48:13,157
Lying to tradesmen,
mending, scratching, scraping.

554
00:48:13,157 --> 00:48:16,661
Endlessly, endlessly making do!

555
00:48:16,661 --> 00:48:19,264
I understand
that our circumstances are difficult, ma'am.

556
00:48:19,264 --> 00:48:23,535
-There is no money for you.
-Surely something could be done.

557
00:48:23,535 --> 00:48:28,406
What we can put by must go to your brothers.
You will have nothing, unless you marry.

558
00:48:28,406 --> 00:48:32,110
Well, then, I will have nothing. For I will not
marry without affection, like my mother!

559
00:48:32,110 --> 00:48:35,386
And now I have to dig my own damn potatoes!

560
00:48:44,622 --> 00:48:50,470
Would you rather be a poor old maid?
Ridiculous, despised, the butt of jokes?

561
00:48:50,929 --> 00:48:55,468
The legitimate sport of any village lout
with a stone and an impudent tongue?

562
00:49:01,739 --> 00:49:05,448
Affection is desirable.

563
00:49:06,711 --> 00:49:10,624
Money is absolutely indispensable.

564
00:49:18,489 --> 00:49:20,127
I could live by my...

565
00:49:24,095 --> 00:49:25,232
Yourwhat?

566
00:49:27,131 --> 00:49:29,235
-I could live by my...
-Pen?

567
00:49:30,268 --> 00:49:33,004
Let's knock that notion on the head
once and for all.

568
00:49:33,004 --> 00:49:34,346
What's this?

569
00:49:34,973 --> 00:49:38,147
Trouble amongst my women?

570
00:49:38,977 --> 00:49:40,148
Come,

571
00:49:41,312 --> 00:49:43,448
take hands and there's an end.

572
00:49:43,448 --> 00:49:46,986
-Where are you going? Miss!
-To feed the pigs, ma'am.

573
00:50:04,802 --> 00:50:06,975
He could give you a splendid home.

574
00:50:08,706 --> 00:50:10,981
-A comfortable life.
-Father.

575
00:50:12,644 --> 00:50:13,713
Consider.

576
00:50:15,013 --> 00:50:17,720
This is likely to be your best offer.

577
00:50:18,349 --> 00:50:19,623
Wisley?

578
00:50:21,185 --> 00:50:23,221
It is true, so far he has not impressed...

579
00:50:23,221 --> 00:50:26,634
-A booby.
-He should grow out ofthat.

580
00:50:40,004 --> 00:50:42,848
Nothing destroys spirit

581
00:50:44,542 --> 00:50:46,043
like poverty.

582
00:50:57,055 --> 00:51:00,900
I saw Queen Marie Antoinette
wear something the same at a ball once.

583
00:51:02,827 --> 00:51:06,570
Am I making a show? I am, I know.

584
00:51:09,901 --> 00:51:13,371
What trouble we take to make them like us
when we like them.

585
00:51:16,340 --> 00:51:17,409
Henry?

586
00:51:20,578 --> 00:51:25,254
-Eliza, my brother is much younger than you.
-And poorer.

587
00:51:28,052 --> 00:51:30,896
He knows that I care for him sincerely.

588
00:51:31,689 --> 00:51:33,424
I know that he is handsome...

589
00:51:33,424 --> 00:51:36,527
And the handsome young men must have
something to live on as well as the plain.

590
00:51:36,527 --> 00:51:38,863
You encourage him to take you for money?

591
00:51:38,863 --> 00:51:41,299
-Men do.
-That does not make it honourable.

592
00:51:41,299 --> 00:51:43,142
Well, I'm a sensible woman.

593
00:51:44,135 --> 00:51:46,740
I thank God I am not, by your description.

594
00:51:48,806 --> 00:51:52,477
Ifyou were, you might have ascertained
that your Irish friend has no money, not a penny

595
00:51:52,477 --> 00:51:55,253
and could not be expected to marry without it.

596
00:51:56,047 --> 00:51:58,221
Consider that at the ball tonight.

597
00:51:59,752 --> 00:52:04,564
In any event, he'll be gone tomorrow back
to Bond Street where he can do no more harm.

598
00:53:57,803 --> 00:53:59,646
Good evening, Miss Austen.

599
00:54:02,040 --> 00:54:03,109
Yes, yes.

600
00:54:43,949 --> 00:54:46,258
(SLOW MUSIC PLAYING)

601
00:57:16,235 --> 00:57:18,681
Miss Jane Austen.

602
00:57:19,272 --> 00:57:20,409
Pleasure.

603
00:57:21,307 --> 00:57:24,515
WOMAN: We're very honoured
to be here at your aunt's ball.

604
00:57:24,744 --> 00:57:26,985
TOM: You dance with passion.

605
00:57:28,114 --> 00:57:33,188
No sensible woman would demonstrate passion
ifthe purpose were to attract a husband.

606
00:57:36,789 --> 00:57:38,996
-As opposed to a lover?
-Hmm.

607
00:57:43,963 --> 00:57:46,299
Rest easy, Mr Lefroy.

608
00:57:46,299 --> 00:57:48,835
-I have no expectation on either account.
-I did not mean to offend or hurt...

609
00:57:48,835 --> 00:57:53,374
Oh, no, no, of course not.
Excuse me, I'm just overwarm.

610
00:57:54,140 --> 00:57:55,277
Pardon me.

611
00:58:06,886 --> 00:58:09,298
-Ah, Miss Austen.
-Excuse me.

612
00:58:44,323 --> 00:58:49,195
HENRY: This is unbearable.
My father is pressing for an early ordination,

613
00:58:49,195 --> 00:58:54,834
while my own inclination is to the scarlet of
a captaincy in His Majesty's regulars.

614
00:58:54,834 --> 00:58:58,543
But I do not have the money to purchase one.

615
00:58:59,872 --> 00:59:01,214
I do.

616
00:59:03,075 --> 00:59:08,684
-Well, that, of course is impossible.
-Oh, Henry, do not disguise yourself, not to me.

617
00:59:12,919 --> 00:59:16,730
The scarlet will suit you very well.

618
00:59:18,624 --> 00:59:22,299
Miss Austen? There you are.

619
00:59:32,705 --> 00:59:37,244
Miss Austen, I cannot believe I am obliged
to have this conversation.

620
00:59:38,644 --> 00:59:39,781
Your Ladyship?

621
00:59:41,314 --> 00:59:45,489
Mr Wisley's mother,
my own dear sister, died young.

622
00:59:46,719 --> 00:59:48,664
I have no children of my own.

623
00:59:49,755 --> 00:59:53,430
I hope you never come to understand
the pain ofthat condition.

624
00:59:55,229 --> 01:00:00,678
Let us simply say my nephew's wishes
are close to my heart,

625
01:00:02,436 --> 01:00:04,813
however extraordinary they may be.

626
01:00:08,175 --> 01:00:09,278
Well,

627
01:00:10,577 --> 01:00:12,750
your health seems robust.

628
01:00:13,914 --> 01:00:16,485
You have the usual accomplishments.

629
01:00:17,651 --> 01:00:20,188
Your person is agreeable.

630
01:00:22,823 --> 01:00:28,195
But when a young woman such as yourself
receives the addresses

631
01:00:28,195 --> 01:00:33,770
from a gentleman such as my nephew,
it is her duty to accept at once.

632
01:00:34,835 --> 01:00:36,473
But what do we find?

633
01:00:38,438 --> 01:00:40,440
-Independent thought?
-Exactly.

634
01:00:41,775 --> 01:00:47,281
My nephew, Miss Austen, condescends far indeed

635
01:00:47,547 --> 01:00:52,386
in offering to the daughter of an obscure
and impecunious clergyman.

636
01:00:52,386 --> 01:00:56,061
Impecunious? Your Ladyship is mistaken.

637
01:00:56,790 --> 01:00:59,031
I am never mistaken.

638
01:01:00,027 --> 01:01:03,975
Your father is in grave financial difficulties.

639
01:01:05,065 --> 01:01:07,044
But all is not lost.

640
01:01:08,502 --> 01:01:12,313
He has a daughter
upon whom fortune has smiled.

641
01:01:27,921 --> 01:01:31,493
Mr Wisley is a good opportunity for Jane.

642
01:01:32,826 --> 01:01:35,169
She should accept him at once.

643
01:01:37,230 --> 01:01:39,903
Do not you think?

644
01:01:40,767 --> 01:01:43,873
-Lucy, let us take some refreshments.
-What? Mother.

645
01:02:10,464 --> 01:02:13,706
I have learned of Mr Wisley's marriage proposal.

646
01:02:15,302 --> 01:02:16,803
My congratulations.

647
01:02:17,404 --> 01:02:22,910
Is there an alternative for
a well-educated young woman of small fortune?

648
01:02:24,211 --> 01:02:25,985
How can you have him?

649
01:02:27,247 --> 01:02:29,383
Even with his thousands and his houses,

650
01:02:29,383 --> 01:02:33,626
how can you, of all people,
dispose ofyourselfwithout affection?

651
01:02:37,424 --> 01:02:40,131
How can I dispose of myselfwith it?

652
01:02:43,063 --> 01:02:45,167
You are leaving tomorrow.

653
01:03:22,536 --> 01:03:25,710
-Did I do that well?
-Very, very well.

654
01:03:26,673 --> 01:03:31,178
I wanted, just once, to do it well.

655
01:03:31,978 --> 01:03:34,788
(MEN CHATTERING)

656
01:03:37,484 --> 01:03:40,720
I have no money, no property,

657
01:03:40,720 --> 01:03:44,524
I am entirely dependent
upon that bizarre old lunatic, my uncle.

658
01:03:44,524 --> 01:03:49,131
I cannot yet offer marriage.
But you must know what I feel.

659
01:03:50,297 --> 01:03:52,003
Jane, I'm yours.

660
01:03:52,866 --> 01:03:57,577
Gah, I'm yours. I'm yours, heart and soul.

661
01:03:59,807 --> 01:04:01,843
Much good that is.

662
01:04:02,844 --> 01:04:04,979
Let me decide that.

663
01:04:04,979 --> 01:04:06,514
(MEN LAUGHING)

664
01:04:10,585 --> 01:04:12,086
What will we do?

665
01:04:15,189 --> 01:04:16,497
What we must.

666
01:04:24,532 --> 01:04:28,469
JANE: "My dearest Cassandra,
my heart has wings.

667
